Yesterday, coming back from visiting a company my dad set me up with, I passed a Lamborghini and a Lotus, one right after the other. Both cars were being driven by guys who looked around 28 years old. Then today I passed a hot pink mercedes-benz with a guy driving it. Not that there is anything wrong with a guy driving it, just not what I expected.

Today was a good day. I went to the beach with Diana, Evan and my dad. I didn't get to stay long as my dad and I needed to get home, so I only had about an hour there, but that was fine with me. I got to boogiboard for the first time in a long time, which was fun. I caught 3 waves and rode 2 of them all the way in until the water wasn't deep enough for me to go any further. After the beach, my dad and I came home and I took a shower and got ready to go to this party I was invited to by a neighbor across the street. It was fun and interesting. I met some nice people and got a couple business cards. Cant go wrong with free drinks and food. I also got to see some cool demonstrations of some 3D programs. My dad has a gig tonight, so i am "baby sitting" Evan until my they get home later. That's all for now.

Just got back from dinner with my dad, Diana and Evan. We went to our local sushi resaurant. We go there so much that we know the owner and all the people who work there. Diana and Evan go there about once a week now according to Evan.

Over 55,000,000 Requests for Citizenship Since Tuesday Night

Canadian immigration officials have reported a huge increase in the number of requests for Canadian citizenship in the past twenty-four hours, with over fifty-five million such inquiries pouring in since late Tuesday night. Of those fifty-five million requests, well over 99.99% of them came from U.S. citizens, the lion's share residing in such states as New York, California, Massachusetts, Oregon, Washington, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Vermont, Maine, Rhode Island, Connecticut, Delaware, Maryland, and the District of Columbia. Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister Pierre Pettigrew said that he was "flabbergasted" by the fifty-five-million-plus requests for Canadian citizenship, adding that it was difficult to pinpoint the precise reasons for the staggering increase. "My only theory is that after many years of exposure in the U.S., hockey is finally starting to catch on," Mr. Pettigrew said. He cautioned, however, that it is impossible to know exactly what is sparking the sudden interest in America's frozen neighbor to the north: "People answering our immigration hotline say that it is hard to understand many of the American callers because they are sobbing uncontrollably." In other news, President Bush used his acceptance speech Wednesday to reach out to supporters of Sen. John Kerry, telling them, "You can run, but you can't hide." Meanwhile, in his first statement since being voted out of office Tuesday night, Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle said, "Do you want fries with that?" Elsewhere, experts said that exit polls may have falsely predicted a Kerry victory because Kerry voters exited while Bush voters stayed behind and voted again.

A computer was something on TV 
From a science fiction show of note 
A window was something you hated to clean 
And ram was the cousin of a goat. 

Meg was the name of my girlfriend 
And gig was a job for the night 
Now they all mean different things 
And that really mega bytes. 

An application was for employment 
A program was a TV show 
A cursor used profanity 
A keyboard was a piano. 

Memory was something that you lost with age 
A CD was a bank account 
And if you had a 3.5-inch floppy 
You hoped nobody found out. 

Compress was something you did to the garbage 
Not something you did to a file 
And if you unzipped anything in public 
You'd be in jail for a while. 

Log on was adding wood to the fire 
Hard drive was a long trip on the road! 
A mouse pad was where a mouse lived 
And a backup happened to your commode. 

Cut you did with a pocket knife 
Paste you did with glue 
A web was a spider's home 
And a virus was the flu. 

I guess I'll stick to my pad and paper 
And the memory in my head 
I hear nobody's been killed in a computer crash 
But when it happens they wish they were dead. 

Author Unknown

My aunt (Mara Zaslove) is a wonderful photographer. She is taking part in a photo contest right now and I would love it if you, the reader of this, could help me. The way a winner is determined is by the number of votes the picture gets. To view the picture: You can view the photo Mara took by going to this web site. At the top of the page, "amateur usa" and "people" are colored red. Click the "places" button right under the "people" button. On the left side of the page, are 8 pictures. Her picture is the bottom right picture ("Sequoias on Fire"). To vote for her picture: Click the "vote" button located at the bottom of the page at the far left. A new window will open and you have to enter your email address as well as select the photograph. Her picture is the very last one on the list. In other news... I am back at school. I just returned from an amazing experience. I spent the last hour in a hot tub on the side of a mountain looking over the ocean. The hot tub is at Esalen in Big Sur. I am so very relaxed. All my muscles have turned into jello for the moment. I love this feeling. I am in Big Sur right now visiting my mom. She recently moved into a little place looking over the ocean. It is one of the most beautiful places I have been, and I have been many places! It is only a one bedroom house with only a bathroom (shower, toilet, sink) and a closet. There is no kitchen, only a mini fridge that is located in the closet, and no seperate bedreoom or anything. There are 3 rooms in the whole place, the bedroom, bathroom, and closet. I am sleeping on an air matress located on the floor. The person who owns the land here is going to renovate this house. Once it is done, it will have a seperate bedroom, a kitchen, and the whole house will be made bigger all around. Once that is done, the place will be very nice.

I have returned from my fabulous extended weekend with Emilie ( <lj user="unkwillow"> ). I had a great time visiting her. I was there from Friday night until Wednesday night. She worked during the day on Saturday, Sunday, and Tuesday. During these days I pretty much hung around the house playing on my computer and hanging out with Tigger (Emilie's new cat, and my old cat :D ). 
On Sunday I cooked a nice meal for Emilie and I. I made 72 market street Meatloaf. It was so good and taisty. I am learing how to cook this summer from my step mom. So far I am doing very well. Its funny, the meatloaf is even better the next day. I love making meatloaf sandwiches with catsup. SO GOOD!
On Monday Emilie "kidnapped" me and we drove out to the coast and Lincoln City. This was kind of a suprised to me as I thought we would go into Portland or something like that. We had lunch at a nice little restaurant called the Wildflower Cafe. The food was excelent. We sat out on the porch which overlooked a little creek. Beyond the creek stood some large trees which were also very pretty. 
After our nice lunch we went further on into Lincoln City to find a used book store owned by a friend of Emilies father. I always love going into used book stores because I can always find obscure books and magazines that I would otherwise not even think existed. I stood around browsing while Emilie did her shopping. She made it out with a few books, which is pretty good considering how dangerous this store is to her wallet. 
Wednesday morning was just a hangout morning. I made eggs in a basket for our breakfast. I got all packed up and we left around 3:15pm for my 6:25pm flight. We did this so we could stop for dinner/lunch (linner or dunch) on the way to PDX. We stopped at Toco Time so Emilie could introdice me to the awesome Veggie Burrito. It is very taisty. 
We then started towards the airport which on a normal occation should take around 45 minutes at the most from where we ate. Well, it actually took us around and hour and a half to make it to the airport. We made it to the airport 10 minutes before my flight was to take off. Luckly I did not have any checked baggage so I ran inside and got my bording pass, ran to security where my backpacked had to be rechecked, and then ran down to my gate which was 3/4 the way down the terminal. I got there just in time to see them close the door to the jetway. I said, "wait, I am on that flight!". It was no problem because there were people still in the jetway getting on the plane. I am still amazed that I somehow made it from the car to my seat on the plane, while getting my backpack checked at secutity and called Emilie to let her know I got on the plane, in a little over 10 minutes. Wow im good! :)
In other news. The fire alarm went off at work yesterday for no reason. We has to leave the building and stand out by the street for 15 minutes or so. Was a nice break but annoying at the same time. 
Thats all for now. Hope all is well with everyone out there in internet land!

p.s. TGIF!
